1
00:00:00,146 --> 00:00:02,258
I said the 20-somethings are dumb. They're not dumb.

2
00:00:02,258 --> 00:00:03,373
It's just certain ways of the world.

3
00:00:03,373 --> 00:00:09,309
The reason I say that, you watch, in the not too distant future, hackers are going to knock out our cellphones and the internet.

4
00:00:09,309 --> 00:00:14,616
These 20-somethings will come to a stop, stare at their phone, and have no idea what to do next.

5
00:00:14,616 --> 00:00:17,583
Because they've always had an internet connection.

6
00:00:17,583 --> 00:00:21,350
If we lose the internet, us old folks, we got a plan B.

7
00:00:21,350 --> 00:00:26,600
You 20-somethings are going to have to find a bunch of old people and ask us how to do stuff.

8
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:28,916
"Hey, mister, can you help me get home? "

9
00:00:28,916 --> 00:00:33,688
I don't know how to do directions."

10
00:00:33,688 --> 00:00:44,327
Well, I can draw you a map but you're gonna have to listen and store the information in your head.

11
00:00:44,327 --> 00:00:48,455
And I'm not here to tell you life was better before cellphones. It wasn't.&nbsp;I love my phone.

12
00:00:48,455 --> 00:00:49,505
I'm addicted to that thing.

13
00:00:49,505 --> 00:00:50,550
You ever lose your phone?

14
00:00:50,550 --> 00:00:53,264
Oh, that's a panic attack.

15
00:00:53,264 --> 00:00:59,867
I lost my kid at the mall one time and didn't panic like that.

16
00:00:59,867 --> 00:01:05,438
Because I have two kids.

17
00:01:05,438 --> 00:01:09,921
Never has technology moved so quickly as the past 20-plus years.

18
00:01:09,921 --> 00:01:11,846
My son was at my house a couple of years ago.

19
00:01:11,846 --> 00:01:13,515
He called my mom, his grandma.

20
00:01:13,515 --> 00:01:15,788
He turns to me, he goes, "I think grandma's phone broken."

21
00:01:15,788 --> 00:01:16,348
I go, why?

22
00:01:16,348 --> 00:01:18,587
He goes, "listen to this."

23
00:01:18,587 --> 00:01:22,347
It's a busy signal.

24
00:01:22,347 --> 00:01:25,048
He'd never heard one.

25
00:01:25,048 --> 00:01:27,540
He goes, "now what do I do?"

26
00:01:27,540 --> 00:01:30,430
Hang up.

27
00:01:30,430 --> 00:01:33,487
He goes, "how do I leave a message?"

28
00:01:33,487 --> 00:01:37,791
You don't.

29
00:01:37,791 --> 00:01:38,694
He goes, "now what do I do?"

30
00:01:38,694 --> 00:01:42,947
I go, wait a few minutes. Call her back.

31
00:01:42,947 --> 00:01:47,030
He goes, "that's stupid."

32
00:01:47,030 --> 00:01:48,366
And I don't know what it was like in your house growing up.

33
00:01:48,366 --> 00:01:51,094
My house growing up, my dad never answered the phone.

34
00:01:51,094 --> 00:01:52,791
He wasn't getting out of his big old chair.

35
00:01:52,791 --> 00:01:54,624
That phone rang, he just looked at us kids.

36
00:01:54,624 --> 00:01:56,678
It was our job to answer the phone, right?

37
00:01:56,678 --> 00:02:11,791
I was telling my son that story one day, he goes, "why didn't you tell your dad to get the phone?"

38
00:02:11,791 --> 00:02:17,648
My World War II marine dad?

39
00:02:17,648 --> 00:02:20,133
I tried it once.

40
00:02:20,133 --> 00:02:24,782
Had no idea he could get out of the chair that quickly.

41
00:02:24,782 --> 00:02:39,002
When I woke up, that phone was inside me.

42
00:02:39,002 --> 00:02:41,952
Here's something that kills me about technology and old people.

43
00:02:41,952 --> 00:02:45,091
By old people, I'm talking about people my age.

44
00:02:45,091 --> 00:02:47,568
Watch us when people are taking pictures.

45
00:02:47,568 --> 00:02:49,151
They've got the camera. We all stop.

46
00:02:49,151 --> 00:02:54,202
We don't walk in front of it because we think we're going to ruin the film.

47
00:02:54,202 --> 00:02:55,930
Hey, Boomer, no more film.

48
00:02:55,930 --> 00:02:58,014
Keep moving.

49
00:02:58,014 --> 00:03:02,067
These guys delete more pictures in an hour than we used to take in a year.

50
00:03:02,067 --> 00:03:03,540
You remember roll of 24?

51
00:03:03,540 --> 00:03:04,563
That thing would last year all year.

52
00:03:04,563 --> 00:03:07,286
You get that back, you go, look, there's Uncle Billy.

53
00:03:07,286 --> 00:03:08,703
He's been dead at least a year.

54
00:03:08,703 --> 00:03:15,297
Oh my. I got some new Uncle Billy photos.

55
00:03:15,297 --> 00:03:18,153
And photos weren't unlimited, you had to keep track.

56
00:03:18,153 --> 00:03:21,963
Remember that little counter on the bottom of the camera told you how many were left?

57
00:03:21,963 --> 00:03:25,174
That's why all the sasquatch photos are crappy.

58
00:03:25,174 --> 00:03:27,418
Everybody was down to their last shot.

59
00:03:27,418 --> 00:03:31,308
Like, oh, there is. Click. Ah.

60
00:03:31,308 --> 00:03:35,310
Behind a tree.&nbsp;

61
00:03:35,310 --> 00:03:38,051
Before COVID, I worked in Singapore and Hong Kong.

62
00:03:38,051 --> 00:03:42,336
I worked these English speaking comedy clubs and I flew from Hong Kong to Singapore on Tigair.

63
00:03:42,336 --> 00:03:45,110
It's this cut rate Asian airline, they cramming you in close together.

64
00:03:45,110 --> 00:03:46,929
And I don't feel like a big man.

65
00:03:46,929 --> 00:03:50,220
But in Asia, I'm gigantic.

66
00:03:50,220 --> 00:03:55,398
I did not realize it till I was standing at the gate looking around going, oh my, I'm the biggest guy here by a lot.

67
00:03:55,398 --> 00:04:06,030
So I'm 6'1", 190. 195. 200. Probably 202 this morning.

68
00:04:06,030 --> 00:04:11,027
Anyway, I was the biggest guy by a lot on the jet and I had a window seat.

69
00:04:11,027 --> 00:04:23,792
There was a guy in the aisle and I said, can I sneak past you?

70
00:04:23,792 --> 00:04:26,292
He said, "your sneaking days are over, my friend."

